00:41:32,730 --> 00:41:35,800
(Suddenly a salmon?)

1046
00:41:37,470 --> 00:41:39,970
- He's filleting the salmon here? - Yes.

1047
00:41:42,740 --> 00:41:47,480
(A rare sight to see in a pastry survival show)

1048
00:41:43,200 --> 00:41:45,240
Seeing this in a baking survival show...

1049
00:41:45,470 --> 00:41:46,980
This is unbelievable.

1050
00:41:48,310 --> 00:41:50,980
I'll show them my national-level skills.

1051
00:41:53,280 --> 00:41:55,280
My goal is to advance to the finals.

1052
00:41:56,750 --> 00:41:59,050
He's the first-generation star chef.

1053
00:41:59,120 --> 00:42:01,420
He practically represents Korea.

1054
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:00,759
(Fine Dining Baker, Yoon Hwa Young from Pres de moi in Cheongdam)

1055
00:42:00,760 --> 00:42:01,920
(The 1st generation of Fine Dining)

1056
00:42:02,520 --> 00:42:05,030
I consider the balance most important.

1057
00:42:05,830 --> 00:42:06,930
I'm confident.

1058
00:42:08,960 --> 00:42:10,329
On "Culinary Class Wars,"

1059
00:42:10,330 --> 00:42:12,970
he started off as a high rank called White Spoon.

1060
00:42:11,400 --> 00:42:12,429
(Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok)

1061
00:42:12,430 --> 00:42:13,670
(24 years of dessert experience, the best vegetable chef in Korea)

1062
00:42:13,870 --> 00:42:15,799
I'll show them what a dessert...

1063
00:42:15,800 --> 00:42:17,910
made by a chef is like.

1064
00:42:19,970 --> 00:42:22,980
I'm An Byeong Tae, and I have 15 years of cooking experience.

1065
00:42:20,480 --> 00:42:21,579
(American Chicken Chef, An Byeong Tae)

1066
00:42:21,580 --> 00:42:22,679
(Donut Drawing, Crac Crack in Bundang)

1067
00:42:22,680 --> 00:42:23,680
(The winner of "Korean Chicken War")

1068
00:42:23,950 --> 00:42:25,079
He was on "Culinary Class Wars."

1069
00:42:24,450 --> 00:42:28,380
(From An Byeong Tae's Instagram account)

1070
00:42:25,080 --> 00:42:27,479
He won on the show "Korean Chicken War."

1071
00:42:27,480 --> 00:42:28,649
- Really? - Yes.

1072
00:42:28,650 --> 00:42:30,990
I may have achieved some level of success as a chef,

1073
00:42:32,120 --> 00:42:34,390
but I believe challenging myself to new things is necessary.

1074
00:42:36,690 --> 00:42:37,860
So I decided to participate.

1075
00:42:39,060 --> 00:42:40,600
He's really cooking.

1076
00:42:40,900 --> 00:42:42,630
He's very serious about it.

1077
00:42:42,730 --> 00:42:44,669
Chefs who cook...

1078
00:42:44,670 --> 00:42:46,070
sure are different.

1079
00:42:46,700 --> 00:42:49,839
Chef Sung Jun, are you keeping an eye on them?

1080
00:42:49,840 --> 00:42:51,809
I sure am, since he cooks.

1081
00:42:51,810 --> 00:42:52,810
Exactly.

1082
00:42:53,040 --> 00:42:55,880
On "Culinary Class Wars," he was put on hold with me.

1083
00:42:56,140 --> 00:42:58,310
He and I sat at the same table for those put on hold.

1084
00:42:58,510 --> 00:42:59,580
That kind of...

1085
00:43:00,420 --> 00:43:01,450
weighs on my mind.

1086
00:43:02,580 --> 00:43:04,650
(Another contender who must be feeling uneasy)

1087
00:43:05,250 --> 00:43:07,919
He is Chef Nam Jeong Seok. He was on "Culinary Class Wars."

1088
00:43:07,920 --> 00:43:09,589
He was on that show.

1089
00:43:09,590 --> 00:43:10,629
It feels rather awkward.

1090
00:43:10,630 --> 00:43:13,260
He started off as a high rank called White Spoon...

1091
00:43:11,960 --> 00:43:13,929
(The contender who was a White Spoon...)

1092
00:43:13,660 --> 00:43:16,760
- I see. - on "Culinary Class Wars."

1093
00:43:13,930 --> 00:43:16,630
(and the master who was a Black Spoon)

1094
00:43:16,830 --> 00:43:17,870
I see.

1095
00:43:19,900 --> 00:43:20,940
(He spots him.)

1096
00:43:19,970 --> 00:43:21,269
- Hello. - Hello.

1097
00:43:21,270 --> 00:43:22,740
- Hello. - I didn't expect to see you here.

1098
00:43:23,100 --> 00:43:24,570
- Neither did I. - Right?

1099
00:43:25,810 --> 00:43:27,080
(An awkward meeting of the two chefs with their positions reversed)

1100
00:43:27,080 --> 00:43:28,380
This is so cruel.

1101
00:43:28,680 --> 00:43:30,179
We used to compete together.

1102
00:43:30,180 --> 00:43:32,709
And he came back as a judge.

1103
00:43:32,710 --> 00:43:34,150
I was so shocked.

1104
00:43:34,550 --> 00:43:36,649
You grow the ingredients yourself, right?

1105
00:43:36,650 --> 00:43:39,320
Yes, all the ones here are grown by me.

1106
00:43:39,520 --> 00:43:40,960
They'll become garnishes.

1107
00:43:39,920 --> 00:43:42,590
(The herbs he grew himself)

1108
00:43:41,190 --> 00:43:43,189
They're all from my garden.

1109
00:43:43,190 --> 00:43:44,260
I look forward to it.

1110
00:43:44,890 --> 00:43:45,930
Thank you.

1111
00:43:46,430 --> 00:43:50,700
Signature means to prepare something you're best at.

1112
00:43:50,930 --> 00:43:53,870
I'm an Italian cuisine chef,

1113
00:43:54,140 --> 00:43:56,369
and I'm the best vegetable chef.

1114
00:43:56,370 --> 00:43:58,570
They all came together and became...

1115
00:43:58,870 --> 00:44:00,710
tomato basil panna cotta.

1116
00:43:59,340 --> 00:44:01,510
(Tomato basil panna cotta)

1117
00:44:01,710 --> 00:44:02,939
"Panna" means "cream,"

1118
00:44:02,110 --> 00:44:03,779
(Panna cotta means to cook cream.)

1119
00:44:02,940 --> 00:44:05,149
and "cotta" means "cooked."

1120
00:44:03,780 --> 00:44:05,980
(It is a pudding or mousse type of dessert.)

1121
00:44:05,150 --> 00:44:06,550
So it means "cooked cream."

1122
00:44:06,650 --> 00:44:08,519
Think of it as milk pudding.

1123
00:44:08,520 --> 00:44:09,550
It's a pudding.

1124
00:44:09,750 --> 00:44:11,350
English-speaking countries call it "pudding."

1125
00:44:09,850 --> 00:44:11,919
(It's called pudding in English-speaking countries...)

1126
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:13,320
Italians call it "panna cotta."

1127
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:13,320
(and panna cotta in Italy.)

1128
00:44:17,060 --> 00:44:18,789
I added parmesan cheese...

1129
00:44:18,790 --> 00:44:21,460
to the panna cotta, so it's sweet and salty.

1130
00:44:21,830 --> 00:44:23,500
I added refreshing tomato jam...

1131
00:44:23,800 --> 00:44:26,570
and the fragrance of basil to it.

1132
00:44:24,900 --> 00:44:27,440
(Basil caviar)

1133
00:44:29,240 --> 00:44:30,969
The dessert I pursue...

1134
00:44:30,970 --> 00:44:32,209
is the type that uses vegetables...

1135
00:44:32,210 --> 00:44:35,710
and is not too sweet.

1136
00:44:35,780 --> 00:44:37,179
"Is this really a dessert?"

1137
00:44:37,180 --> 00:44:38,809
"Is this food or dessert?"

1138
00:44:38,810 --> 00:44:40,680
I wonder how they'll evaluate that.

1139
00:44:40,780 --> 00:44:43,420
I'm excited and worried at the same time.

1140
00:44:45,320 --> 00:44:48,490
(Chef An Byeong Tae enters first.)

1141
00:44:51,830 --> 00:44:54,700
(His signature bread is ready.)

1142
00:44:56,630 --> 00:44:59,470
(Crack baguette)

1143
00:44:57,670 --> 00:44:59,599
My signature bread is called crack baguette.

1144
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:01,599
I made the original multigrain baguette...

1145
00:45:01,600 --> 00:45:03,169
a lot crustier.

1146
00:45:03,170 --> 00:45:04,710
It's a grilled vegetable sandwich.

1147
00:45:05,340 --> 00:45:07,109
It has two kicks to it.

1148
00:45:07,110 --> 00:45:09,939
The crustiness you feel when you take a bite is the first kick.

1149
00:45:09,940 --> 00:45:13,209
The second kick is, one of the ingredients used...

1150
00:45:13,210 --> 00:45:14,850
is jalapeno jam.

1151
00:45:15,280 --> 00:45:17,949
That ingredient brings together all the other ingredients.

1152
00:45:15,380 --> 00:45:19,590
(Jalapeno jam)

1153
00:45:17,950 --> 00:45:19,220
That's the second kick.

1154
00:45:21,860 --> 00:45:24,890
- It feels like banh mi. - It's like banh mi.

1155
00:45:26,030 --> 00:45:27,530
When I touch it... My gosh.

1156
00:45:27,900 --> 00:45:29,600
(The sandwich reminds them of banh mi.)

1157
00:45:30,200 --> 00:45:31,930
(Crusty)

1158
00:45:39,970 --> 00:45:42,110
(French ham)

1159
00:45:45,450 --> 00:45:48,050
(Master Kwon Sung Jun's expression changes rapidly.)

1160
00:45:50,220 --> 00:45:51,450
Which ham did you use?

1161
00:45:51,790 --> 00:45:54,490
It's French ham. We sous-vide it ourselves.

1162
00:45:55,120 --> 00:45:57,759
Besides sous-vide, it seems to be slightly cooked on the surface.

1163
00:45:57,760 --> 00:46:00,089
That must've been from the torch I used just now.

1164
00:46:00,090 --> 00:46:01,329
- You torched it? - Briefly.

1165
00:46:01,330 --> 00:46:02,799
You sous-vide it, and then torched it?

1166
00:46:02,800 --> 00:46:03,830
That's right.

1167
00:46:06,830 --> 00:46:09,370
(What will become of American Chicken Chef?)

1168
00:46:06,830 --> 00:46:08,040
Something's wrong.

1169
00:46:09,940 --> 00:46:11,540
Here it comes.

1170
00:46:13,010 --> 00:46:14,209
- The salmon is here. - Yes.

1171
00:46:14,210 --> 00:46:17,550
National Level Chef, Yoon Jong Chan.

1172
00:46:16,040 --> 00:46:17,279
(National Level Chef, Yoon Jong Chan)

1173
00:46:17,280 --> 00:46:18,410
(The head chef of Taereung Training Center)

1174
00:46:18,510 --> 00:46:20,720
There are three versions?

1175
00:46:21,680 --> 00:46:24,650
I wanted to show you as many as I could with one salmon.

1176
00:46:24,750 --> 00:46:26,390
They're salmon open sandwich...

1177
00:46:25,220 --> 00:46:27,259
(K-salmon open sandwich...)

1178
00:46:27,260 --> 00:46:29,860
(and salmon steak)

1179
00:46:27,290 --> 00:46:29,760
and salmon steak.

1180
00:46:30,390 --> 00:46:33,630
How did you season the salmon steak? Or did you apply a sauce?

1181
00:46:34,060 --> 00:46:36,499
I made it like grilled doenjang salmon.

1182
00:46:36,500 --> 00:46:39,570
I used doenjang and whole grain mustard...

1183
00:46:39,600 --> 00:46:42,139
as the basic sauce,

1184
00:46:42,140 --> 00:46:44,169
and seasoned it with a bit of salt.

1185
00:46:44,170 --> 00:46:45,240
A bit of salt?

1186
00:46:50,750 --> 00:46:55,050
I added doenjang so it tastes both Korean and western.

1187
00:46:50,810 --> 00:46:55,050
(Master Kwon Sung Jun tastes each ingredient first.)

1188
00:46:57,520 --> 00:46:58,550
(Frowning)

1189
00:47:01,160 --> 00:47:05,089
As for the whole bread,

1190
00:47:05,090 --> 00:47:08,060
you can have it with the salmon steak.

1191
00:47:08,360 --> 00:47:10,799
As for the open sandwich,

1192
00:47:10,800 --> 00:47:13,130
please have it with the raw salmon placed on it.

1193
00:47:22,440 --> 00:47:24,810
(The open sandwich is hard to eat.)

1194
00:47:26,380 --> 00:47:30,820
If I add too much, it will become...

1195
00:47:30,950 --> 00:47:33,390
(In the end, he puts down his fork.)

1196
00:47:36,790 --> 00:47:38,290
If the bread was the main subject...

1197
00:47:38,390 --> 00:47:39,460
I see.

1198
00:47:39,730 --> 00:47:42,260
And the salmon blended in as a side ingredient,

1199
00:47:43,900 --> 00:47:45,170
But it feels like salmon became the main dish...

1200
00:47:47,840 --> 00:47:49,839
- Is that so? - You said...

1201
00:47:49,840 --> 00:47:51,510
- the food became the main subject. - Yes.

1202
00:47:51,610 --> 00:47:53,070
For me, the food...

1203
00:47:55,410 --> 00:47:58,210
is not seasoned properly, and the taste isn't balanced.

1204
00:48:01,220 --> 00:48:02,820
(National Level Chef, Yoon Jong Chan failed.)

1205
00:48:01,780 --> 00:48:04,490
Contender Yoon Jong Chan, you have failed.

1206
00:48:05,950 --> 00:48:08,290
American Chicken Chef, you have failed.

1207
00:48:06,350 --> 00:48:08,520
(American Chicken Chef, An Byeong Tae failed.)

1208
00:48:10,220 --> 00:48:11,660
It's because of Kwon Sung Jun.

1209
00:48:11,790 --> 00:48:14,500
(As a professional cooking chef, Master Sung Jun judged strictly.)

1210
00:48:11,860 --> 00:48:13,690
We were both put on hold back then.

1211
00:48:15,200 --> 00:48:17,229
The evaluation was very strict.

1212
00:48:17,230 --> 00:48:19,470
Frankly, I didn't expect to fail.

1213
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:22,870
(He shows no mercy for food-like pastries.)

1214
00:48:23,240 --> 00:48:26,210
It was tasty, but it felt like the salmon overshadowed the bread.

1215
00:48:26,510 --> 00:48:28,039
- The bread wasn't visible. - Yes.

1216
00:48:28,040 --> 00:48:29,410
I don't remember how the bread tasted.

1217
00:48:30,040 --> 00:48:31,809
When chefs bake bread,

1218
00:48:31,810 --> 00:48:33,850
they should focus on the bread itself even more.

1219
00:48:33,980 --> 00:48:37,080
But they keep trying to make a dish out of the bread they've baked.

1220
00:48:37,180 --> 00:48:40,590
So they tend to go off track.

1221
00:48:40,690 --> 00:48:41,720
Yes.

1222
00:48:44,130 --> 00:48:46,229
He's the first-generation star chef.

1223
00:48:44,160 --> 00:48:47,130
(The 1st generation star chef)

1224
00:48:46,230 --> 00:48:47,460
A star chef?

1225
00:48:47,960 --> 00:48:49,159
(The 1st generation of fine dining chefs...)

1226
00:48:48,230 --> 00:48:49,700
He does French cuisine.

1227
00:48:49,160 --> 00:48:50,530
(who studied in France)

1228
00:48:50,630 --> 00:48:52,499
(Contender Yoon Hwa Young is admired by Michelin-star chefs.)

1229
00:48:50,630 --> 00:48:52,429
In the field of fine dining...

1230
00:48:52,430 --> 00:48:54,300
- He's like the godfather. - Yes.

1231
00:48:52,500 --> 00:48:54,640
(The youngest 1-star, Lee Choong Hu, Michelin 3-star, Anh Sung Jae)

1232
00:48:55,440 --> 00:48:57,640
He's participating as a pastry chef.

1233
00:48:57,840 --> 00:48:59,909
In the pastry industry,

1234
00:48:59,910 --> 00:49:02,010
I'm the novice of all novices.

1235
00:49:02,580 --> 00:49:05,280
I wanted to learn more, so I decided to participate.

1236
00:49:06,380 --> 00:49:09,450
(What's the signature bread of Contender Yoon Hwa Young?)

1237
00:49:10,120 --> 00:49:12,349
I'll make a sandwich...

1238
00:49:10,220 --> 00:49:12,089
(Whole wheat campagne)

1239
00:49:12,090 --> 00:49:14,059
(Healthy, country-style French bread...)

1240
00:49:12,350 --> 00:49:14,360
using whole wheat campagne sourdough.

1241
00:49:14,060 --> 00:49:17,120
(which mainly uses whole wheat powder)

1242
00:49:14,920 --> 00:49:17,189
As for my sandwich,

1243
00:49:17,190 --> 00:49:18,760
the key is the bread.

1244
00:49:19,890 --> 00:49:22,229
I fermented the dough for 25 hours.

1245
00:49:22,230 --> 00:49:25,470
I pay attention to certain details when I make the sourdough starter.

1246
00:49:26,770 --> 00:49:31,039
(The dough which was fermented for 25 hours...)

1247
00:49:31,040 --> 00:49:33,470
(enters the oven.)

1248
00:49:38,310 --> 00:49:40,050
(Silent)

1249
00:49:40,150 --> 00:49:41,450
It didn't steam, did it?

1250
00:49:43,150 --> 00:49:45,189
When the dough starts to bake, it needs to produce steam.

1251
00:49:45,190 --> 00:49:47,859
That happens in the first five seconds.

1252
00:49:47,860 --> 00:49:50,420
If it doesn't steam, you can't use that bread.

1253
00:49:50,960 --> 00:49:54,330
(The dough in the oven shows no reaction.)

1254
00:49:55,600 --> 00:49:57,060
(Darn it.)

1255
00:49:55,800 --> 00:49:57,060
Darn it.

1256
00:49:58,400 --> 00:49:59,800
(Sighing)

1257
00:49:59,930 --> 00:50:02,270
Chef Yoon Hwa Young must be facing an issue.

1258
00:50:02,540 --> 00:50:03,570
What?

1259
00:50:03,840 --> 00:50:06,140
He doesn't look too happy.

1260
00:50:06,340 --> 00:50:07,380
What's wrong?

1261
00:50:08,180 --> 00:50:09,340
It won't steam.

1262
00:50:10,080 --> 00:50:11,250
- It won't steam? - No.

1263
00:50:12,180 --> 00:50:13,750
(Contender Yoon Hwa Young becomes busy.)

1264
00:50:14,380 --> 00:50:16,550
(He quickly pours water to produce steam.)

1265
00:50:17,450 --> 00:50:18,720
This is driving me insane.

1266
00:50:21,190 --> 00:50:23,489
For hard bread like that, it needs to produce steam.

1267
00:50:23,490 --> 00:50:25,260
If it doesn't, it becomes very tough.

1268
00:50:25,960 --> 00:50:27,189
The bread will definitely fail.

1269
00:50:27,190 --> 00:50:29,529
You can't bake proper bread like that.

1270
00:50:29,530 --> 00:50:31,669
There are many variables.

1271
00:50:31,670 --> 00:50:34,669
They're in a different setting from their workshops.

1272
00:50:34,670 --> 00:50:36,839
Who adjusts first is important in a survival show.

1273
00:50:36,840 --> 00:50:38,539
He might not even make it here.

1274
00:50:38,540 --> 00:50:40,670
If he himself thinks...

1275
00:50:40,980 --> 00:50:42,779
the bread is ruined,

1276
00:50:42,740 --> 00:50:44,879
(He might not even enter the evaluation room...)

1277
00:50:42,780 --> 00:50:44,209
he might not even want to get evaluated.

1278
00:50:44,210 --> 00:50:45,950
He might not want to because of his pride.

1279
00:50:44,880 --> 00:50:46,650
(because of his pride.)

1280
00:50:48,420 --> 00:50:50,149
I've never used...

1281
00:50:50,150 --> 00:50:51,849
the new equipment before.

1282
00:50:51,850 --> 00:50:53,990
Honestly, there are so many things I don't know about it.

1283
00:50:56,390 --> 00:50:59,959
You have no idea how the oven works until the bread is baked.

1284
00:50:59,960 --> 00:51:01,429
So I kept changing the temperature of the oven...

1285
00:51:01,430 --> 00:51:03,530
and sat right next to the oven door.

1286
00:51:04,060 --> 00:51:06,969
I stared at it as if it was my first time...

1287
00:51:06,970 --> 00:51:08,540
using an oven.

1288
00:51:10,200 --> 00:51:13,210
(After the ups and downs, did the bread come out well?)

1289
00:51:13,740 --> 00:51:15,010
(Knocking)

1290
00:51:15,240 --> 00:51:17,010
Do you knock on it to check?

1291
00:51:17,610 --> 00:51:20,179
Well-baked sourdough...

1292
00:51:20,180 --> 00:51:21,350
makes an empty sound when knocked.

1293
00:51:21,980 --> 00:51:23,850
(He checks if it makes the empty sound.)

1294
00:51:23,750 --> 00:51:24,820
It's like a watermelon.

1295
00:51:27,250 --> 00:51:28,960
(Impressed)

1296
00:51:27,960 --> 00:51:29,560
It looks good.

1297
00:51:29,760 --> 00:51:31,960
(Thanks to the added steam, the bread is shaped nicely.)

1298
00:51:30,120 --> 00:51:32,260
- Gosh, it looks so delicious. - It looks delicious.

1299
00:51:32,730 --> 00:51:34,400
He sure is experienced.

1300
00:51:34,660 --> 00:51:36,159
But if he wants to make sandwiches,

1301
00:51:36,160 --> 00:51:37,969
- he has a lot to do. - That's right.

1302
00:51:37,970 --> 00:51:39,070
The time left...

1303
00:51:43,700 --> 00:51:44,910
What is he doing?

1304
00:51:45,270 --> 00:51:46,440
The temperature of the bread.

1305
00:51:46,640 --> 00:51:49,980
To make a sandwich, you need to cut the bread.

1306
00:51:50,280 --> 00:51:52,109
If you cut the bread while it's still hot,

1307
00:51:52,110 --> 00:51:55,980
moisture starts to evaporate from the cut surface.

1308
00:51:56,250 --> 00:51:59,550
Then that surface dries up and becomes very rough.

1309
00:51:59,790 --> 00:52:01,859
I had to cut the bread...

1310
00:52:00,150 --> 00:52:01,619
(Although it hasn't cooled down yet,)

1311
00:52:01,620 --> 00:52:03,490
(he starts making sandwiches since he is running out of time.)

1312
00:52:01,860 --> 00:52:03,360
which hadn't completely cooled down.

1313
00:52:05,090 --> 00:52:08,630
(The bread, which wasn't baked in the best condition, is cut.)

1314
00:52:11,870 --> 00:52:16,000
(He swiftly works on his sandwiches using his skills.)

1315
00:52:20,210 --> 00:52:23,780
(Contender Yoon Hwa Young hurriedly finishes up.)

1316
00:52:27,210 --> 00:52:28,720
I braced myself and went in.

1317
00:52:33,690 --> 00:52:34,890
Here it comes.

1318
00:52:36,290 --> 00:52:38,090
(Fine Dining Baker, Yoon Hwa Young)

1319
00:52:38,530 --> 00:52:41,599
Hello. I've cooked and baked for 25 years.

1320
00:52:40,490 --> 00:52:41,759
(Fine Dining Baker, Yoon Hwa Young)

1321
00:52:41,600 --> 00:52:42,729
I'm Yoon Hwa Young.

1322
00:52:41,760 --> 00:52:43,129
(Pres de moi in Cheongdam)

1323
00:52:42,730 --> 00:52:45,500
I run a sandwich shop named Pres de moi in Cheongdam-dong.

1324
00:52:43,130 --> 00:52:44,429
(The 1st generation of Fine Dining)

1325
00:52:44,430 --> 00:52:45,600
(Selected as top 1,000 restaurants worldwide by "La Liste")

1326
00:52:45,800 --> 00:52:47,069
We make sandwiches...

1327
00:52:47,070 --> 00:52:49,300
using the bread we bake ourselves.

1328
00:52:52,370 --> 00:52:54,809
As a chef, I wanted to suggest...

1329
00:52:54,810 --> 00:52:56,980
a sandwich with a good balance of carbs, protein, and fats.

1330
00:52:55,080 --> 00:52:57,280
(Reuben sandwich)

1331
00:52:57,110 --> 00:52:58,449
At the bottom of the sandwich...

1332
00:52:58,450 --> 00:53:02,350
is the sauce Russian dressing.

1333
00:53:02,450 --> 00:53:05,790
And there are onions, pickles, and sriracha.

1334
00:53:05,950 --> 00:53:08,559
The choucroute was fermented for one month.

1335
00:53:08,560 --> 00:53:10,789
Except the cheese, 99 percent of the ingredients used...

1336
00:53:08,560 --> 00:53:10,289
(Whole wheat campagne, emmental cheese,)

1337
00:53:10,290 --> 00:53:12,830
(corned beef, choucroute)

1338
00:53:10,790 --> 00:53:12,730
are made by ourselves.

1339
00:53:12,930 --> 00:53:15,800
We're more of a restaurant than a bakery,

1340
00:53:15,900 --> 00:53:17,670
so we make our sandwiches as such.

1341
00:53:19,530 --> 00:53:23,040
Shall we taste it and share our thoughts?

1342
00:53:36,680 --> 00:53:38,889
(So far, none of the chefs' sandwiches...)

1343
00:53:38,890 --> 00:53:41,320
(passed the evaluation.)

1344
00:53:44,430 --> 00:53:47,530
(What about Contender Hwa Young's sandwich?)

1345
00:53:59,440 --> 00:54:00,980
(Oh, no.)

1346
00:54:02,110 --> 00:54:04,409
I had to cut the bread while it was still hot,

1347
00:54:04,410 --> 00:54:05,779
so it's a bit thick.

1348
00:54:05,780 --> 00:54:07,719
Have you been in a competition?

1349
00:54:07,720 --> 00:54:08,820
This is my first.

1350
00:54:09,350 --> 00:54:12,090
(A veteran chef's first survival show)

1351
00:54:14,920 --> 00:54:19,690
Many of your competitors...

1352
00:54:20,490 --> 00:54:23,029
made sandwiches.

1353
00:54:23,030 --> 00:54:24,030
Yes.

1354
00:54:25,170 --> 00:54:26,399
They didn't blend well...

1355
00:54:26,400 --> 00:54:28,570
because they overdid it with the ingredients.

1356
00:54:29,040 --> 00:54:30,569
I couldn't give them high scores...

1357
00:54:30,570 --> 00:54:33,140
because they didn't blend well.

1358
00:54:33,570 --> 00:54:34,610
I see.

1359
00:54:36,210 --> 00:54:38,709
I'm sure I lack in certain aspects.

1360
00:54:38,710 --> 00:54:40,880
Many things didn't go my way during the baking process.

1361
00:54:40,980 --> 00:54:44,420
So it's quite a bummer.

1362
00:54:41,580 --> 00:54:44,750
(Will Fine Dining Baker be all right?)

1363
00:54:47,320 --> 00:54:49,719
Masters, if you're done eating,

1364
00:54:49,720 --> 00:54:51,960
please start voting.

1365
00:54:54,260 --> 00:54:57,930
(It is hard to guess the result based on their expressions.)

1366
00:55:00,030 --> 00:55:03,140
Fine Dining Baker, Yoon Hwa Young.

1367
00:55:00,170 --> 00:55:05,010
(Can the 1st generation chef protect his pride?)

1368
00:55:03,570 --> 00:55:06,170
Let's check the result.

1369
00:55:06,740 --> 00:55:09,440
If the conveyor belt stops, you pass.

1370
00:55:08,640 --> 00:55:10,410
(Pass?)

1371
00:55:10,440 --> 00:55:13,310
If the conveyor belt keeps moving without stopping, you fail.

1372
00:55:12,450 --> 00:55:14,350
(Fail?)

1373
00:55:17,820 --> 00:55:19,590
I didn't serve them my best sandwich.

1374
00:55:19,850 --> 00:55:21,390
That's such a bummer.

1375
00:55:28,100 --> 00:55:29,800
(Fine Dining Baker, Yoon Hwa Young, passed.)

1376
00:55:30,260 --> 00:55:32,529
Contender Yoon Hwa Young, you have passed.

1377
00:55:32,530 --> 00:55:33,670
Congratulations.

1378
00:55:33,830 --> 00:55:35,300
(Thumbs up)

1379
00:55:33,970 --> 00:55:35,070
It was so delicious.

1380
00:55:35,370 --> 00:55:39,940
You made such a proper sourdough.

1381
00:55:40,310 --> 00:55:44,850
All the ingredients blended in so well.

1382
00:55:45,110 --> 00:55:47,550
I took a bite, and it was delicious.

1383
00:55:47,980 --> 00:55:50,249
If a chef is good at baking too,

1384
00:55:50,250 --> 00:55:51,790
how will people like us survive?

1385
00:55:52,050 --> 00:55:53,990
(Master Lee Seok Won's high praise)

1386
00:55:54,390 --> 00:55:55,490
You finished it.

1387
00:55:55,560 --> 00:55:57,859
- Chef Kwon Sung Ju finished it. - You finished it.

1388
00:55:56,120 --> 00:55:58,060
(He finished his sandwich.)

1389
00:55:57,860 --> 00:56:01,199
He is Korea's representative chef,

1390
00:56:01,200 --> 00:56:03,030
and I want to applaud him just for deciding to come here.

1391
00:56:04,030 --> 00:56:07,630
The food was so good that I don't even dare evaluate it.

1392
00:56:07,900 --> 00:56:09,070
Thanks for the good food.

1393
00:56:09,840 --> 00:56:10,870
Thank you.

1394
00:56:11,440 --> 00:56:12,740
It was really tasty.

1395
00:56:13,510 --> 00:56:14,910
This is just the start.

1396
00:56:15,310 --> 00:56:16,940
I'll go home, study more,

1397
00:56:17,410 --> 00:56:20,750
and practice and prepare more...

1398
00:56:21,220 --> 00:56:23,680
so that I won't become a nuisance to other contenders.

1399
00:56:23,780 --> 00:56:24,989
- Thank you. - Thank you.

1400
00:56:24,990 --> 00:56:26,020
Thank you.

1401
00:56:25,690 --> 00:56:28,220
(The first chef to pass with his sandwich)

1402
00:56:28,690 --> 00:56:29,960
I'm taking this home.

1403
00:56:30,690 --> 00:56:31,960
He should just stick to cooking.

1404
00:56:30,760 --> 00:56:32,690
(The baking rival makes him nervous.)

1405
00:56:35,700 --> 00:56:38,730
(The next contender to head to the evaluation room)

1406
00:56:39,470 --> 00:56:41,400
- You can do it. - You can do it.

1407
00:56:41,900 --> 00:56:44,570
(Another chef who gave it a go at making desserts)

1408
00:56:45,010 --> 00:56:47,940
I'll become number one at vegetable desserts.

1409
00:56:49,540 --> 00:56:51,810
(Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok)

1410
00:56:55,020 --> 00:56:58,190
(Tomato basil panna cotta)

1411
00:56:59,520 --> 00:57:00,990
It's my first time seeing such dessert.

1412
00:57:01,660 --> 00:57:03,889
(Savory dessert)

1413
00:57:01,690 --> 00:57:02,859
It's called savoury dessert.

1414
00:57:02,860 --> 00:57:05,929
It's a dessert which uses cooking ingredients.

1415
00:57:03,890 --> 00:57:05,359
(A non-sweet dessert which is salty or savory...)

1416
00:57:05,360 --> 00:57:06,860
(made using cooking ingredients)

1417
00:57:05,930 --> 00:57:06,959
It looks like proper food.

1418
00:57:06,960 --> 00:57:09,799
It's a dessert typically made by chefs.

1419
00:57:09,800 --> 00:57:10,859
I see.

1420
00:57:10,860 --> 00:57:11,929
- Is that so? - It's like food.

1421
00:57:10,930 --> 00:57:13,800
(The kind of dessert that portrays their cooking style)

1422
00:57:11,930 --> 00:57:12,970
It's like food.

1423
00:57:13,800 --> 00:57:14,970
I see.

1424
00:57:15,340 --> 00:57:17,670
Hello, I was on "Culinary Class Wars..."

1425
00:57:18,210 --> 00:57:20,070
as the best vegetable chef.

1426
00:57:18,340 --> 00:57:20,109
(Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok)

1427
00:57:20,110 --> 00:57:21,980
(24 years of dessert experience, the best vegetable chef in Korea)

1428
00:57:20,270 --> 00:57:21,940
I'm Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok.

1429
00:57:23,780 --> 00:57:26,010
(It feels awkward to judge you.)

1430
00:57:23,910 --> 00:57:24,980
It feels awkward.

1431
00:57:27,650 --> 00:57:30,650
I believe Chef Kwon Sung Jun...

1432
00:57:30,850 --> 00:57:36,090
would evaluate my dessert better as a chef himself.

1433
00:57:37,690 --> 00:57:40,160
(It's their first time trying this type of dessert.)

1434
00:57:54,510 --> 00:57:56,180
I've never tasted something like this before.

1435
00:57:56,510 --> 00:57:57,849
At first, it felt too foreign.

1436
00:57:57,850 --> 00:58:00,209
"Is this food or dessert?"

1437
00:58:00,210 --> 00:58:02,820
Then I had another bite with the chocolate.

1438
00:58:00,980 --> 00:58:04,350
(Chocolate croustillant)

1439
00:58:02,980 --> 00:58:04,319
Then I tried just the top part.

1440
00:58:04,320 --> 00:58:06,890
It felt like I was eating a pudding.

1441
00:58:07,150 --> 00:58:09,319
I enjoyed it.

1442
00:58:09,320 --> 00:58:10,920
- Thank you. - Thank you.

1443
00:58:12,190 --> 00:58:14,159
Among savoury desserts,

1444
00:58:14,160 --> 00:58:17,029
the ones that use Italian ingredients...

1445
00:58:17,030 --> 00:58:18,669
are really difficult to make.

1446
00:58:18,670 --> 00:58:20,800
- I see. - I've tried it many times too.

1447
00:58:21,130 --> 00:58:23,100
This must've been a difficult challenge.

1448
00:58:25,840 --> 00:58:28,279
Panna cotta, basil, and tomato...

1449
00:58:28,280 --> 00:58:30,510
are all very intricate ingredients.

1450
00:58:30,940 --> 00:58:32,309
- Yes. - The balance...

1451
00:58:32,310 --> 00:58:33,880
you've made very intricately...

1452
00:58:36,420 --> 00:58:38,650
is ruined by the chocolate in a way.

1453
00:58:39,050 --> 00:58:42,590
The chocolate flavour covers up all the other flavours.

1454
00:58:42,760 --> 00:58:44,490
The chocolate stands out too much.

1455
00:58:44,960 --> 00:58:47,430
- I see. - It's such an intricate dish,

1456
00:58:47,760 --> 00:58:49,060
but the chocolate is a shame.

1457
00:58:49,530 --> 00:58:51,370
(The chocolate ruined the balance.)

1458
00:58:51,160 --> 00:58:53,969
I don't feel offended.

1459
00:58:53,970 --> 00:58:55,170
I'm just upset I couldn't do better.

1460
00:58:56,800 --> 00:58:59,610
Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok.

1461
00:58:59,910 --> 00:59:02,510
(Will he pass?)

1462
00:59:00,110 --> 00:59:02,710
Let's check the result.

1463
00:59:03,140 --> 00:59:06,450
If the conveyor belt stops, you pass.

1464
00:59:06,780 --> 00:59:08,450
If the conveyor belt keeps moving without stopping, you fail.

1465
00:59:09,350 --> 00:59:14,390
(What's the result of Contender Nam Jeong Seok?)

1466
00:59:10,580 --> 00:59:13,950
What's the result?

1467
00:59:23,730 --> 00:59:25,830
(Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok, failed.)

1468
00:59:28,670 --> 00:59:32,140
Unfortunately, Nam Jeong Seok, you have failed.

1469
00:59:34,740 --> 00:59:35,740
Yes.

1470
00:59:34,940 --> 00:59:36,910
(Sighing)

1471
00:59:37,780 --> 00:59:39,550
- I'll work harder. - Okay.

1472
00:59:39,610 --> 00:59:41,209
- Thank you. - Contender Nam Jeong Seok.

1473
00:59:41,210 --> 00:59:43,780
We'll root for you. Thank you for your hard work.

1474
00:59:44,380 --> 00:59:46,390
- Good job. - Thank you.

1475
00:59:46,850 --> 00:59:49,789
(It's a pity, but they must be very strict.)

1476
00:59:49,790 --> 00:59:52,690
(Culinary Pastry Chef, Nam Jeong Seok, failed.)

1477
00:59:54,230 --> 00:59:55,359
My goodness.

1478
00:59:54,460 --> 00:59:57,060
(The contender thought to be the top contender failed.)

1479
00:59:55,360 --> 00:59:56,930
- Really? - No way.

1480
00:59:58,330 --> 01:00:00,200
(The contenders are in shock.)

1481
01:00:00,700 --> 01:00:01,900
(Unbelievable)

1482
01:00:01,970 --> 01:00:03,340
I didn't expect this.

1483
01:00:03,670 --> 01:00:05,369
"I might fail at this rate too."

1484
01:00:05,370 --> 01:00:07,470
I started thinking that.

1485
01:00:07,980 --> 01:00:10,510
That thought made me feel at ease.

1486
01:00:10,580 --> 01:00:12,879
So many experts have failed,

1487
01:00:12,880 --> 01:00:14,210
which means I stand no chance.

1488
01:00:17,380 --> 01:00:18,990
She is Queen of Donuts.

1489
01:00:21,020 --> 01:00:22,390
She's the first contender to make donuts, right?

1490
01:00:22,690 --> 01:00:24,260
- That's right. - The first donut.

1491
01:00:22,920 --> 01:00:24,320
(The first contender to make donuts)

1492
01:00:26,130 --> 01:00:28,160
She rolls them using both hands.

1493
01:00:28,530 --> 01:00:30,200
- She places them nicely. - Nicely.

1494
01:00:29,700 --> 01:00:31,130
(Lining them up)

1495
01:00:33,270 --> 01:00:35,870
I am Queen of Donuts, Jae In Young.

1496
01:00:34,300 --> 01:00:35,499
(Queen of Donuts, Jae In Young from Bins Ring in Nowon)

1497
01:00:35,500 --> 01:00:36,670
(Studied in Ecole De Patisserie De Tokyo)

1498
01:00:37,340 --> 01:00:40,170
(The contender's donut shop is in Nowon.)

1499
01:00:37,470 --> 01:00:40,209
I run a donut shop.

1500
01:00:40,210 --> 01:00:41,540
The shop and home.

1501
01:00:42,040 --> 01:00:44,239
I go to and fro these two places.

1502
01:00:44,240 --> 01:00:46,509
I don't even have time to rest alone,

1503
01:00:46,510 --> 01:00:48,720
which means I don't have time to meet other pastry chefs.

1504
01:00:49,180 --> 01:00:51,690
I run a small shop.

1505
01:00:52,150 --> 01:00:53,419
"Even when I feel tired,"

1506
01:00:53,420 --> 01:00:56,059
"I'll work harder for my husband and my son."

1507
01:00:56,060 --> 01:00:58,060
They make me think that way.

1508
01:00:58,260 --> 01:01:00,159
They're the biggest motivation...

1509
01:01:00,160 --> 01:01:01,860
that kept me going at work.

1510
01:01:03,060 --> 01:01:05,670
(She runs her donut shop for her family.)

1511
01:01:06,930 --> 01:01:09,740
(What kind of donuts will the Queen of Donuts show us?)

1512
01:01:10,070 --> 01:01:11,810
(Putting in the donut dough)

1513
01:01:10,070 --> 01:01:11,200
The donuts enter.

1514
01:01:12,040 --> 01:01:13,610
They taste best when fresh.

1515
01:01:17,280 --> 01:01:18,750
They look tasty.

1516
01:01:19,680 --> 01:01:21,719
Everything tastes good when deep-fried.

1517
01:01:21,720 --> 01:01:22,850
Even shoes taste good that way.

1518
01:01:22,080 --> 01:01:24,380
(Everyone knows deep-frying makes everything taste better.)

1519
01:01:24,850 --> 01:01:26,550
They look so pretty.

1520
01:01:26,650 --> 01:01:28,420
Don't they look like Anpanman's cheeks?

1521
01:01:28,520 --> 01:01:30,090
I know, right? They're so cute.

1522
01:01:31,120 --> 01:01:33,490
(Time to show off her freshly-fried donuts)

1523
01:01:31,260 --> 01:01:32,359
- My gosh. - Aren't they cute?

1524
01:01:32,360 --> 01:01:33,560
- Aren't they so cute? - You only get this...

1525
01:01:34,460 --> 01:01:36,560
(Only well-fried donuts have the line in the middle.)

1526
01:01:34,630 --> 01:01:36,530
- The line in the middle. Right? - It's nothing.

1527
01:01:36,900 --> 01:01:37,929
They're so cute.

1528
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:39,170
(The donuts are attracting everyone's attention.)

1529
01:01:37,930 --> 01:01:39,070
- Aren't they cute? - Yes.

1530
01:01:39,200 --> 01:01:40,300
My babies.

1531
01:01:42,240 --> 01:01:44,270
Bread is like my baby.

1532
01:01:44,810 --> 01:01:46,570
I'm on the show with my babies.

1533
01:01:46,770 --> 01:01:49,840
I'm a bit scared as to how they'll evaluate the donuts.

1534
01:01:50,180 --> 01:01:51,709
On the other hand, if they approve,

1535
01:01:51,710 --> 01:01:53,609
it would make me so happy.

1536
01:01:53,610 --> 01:01:56,380
I'm feeling both excited and nervous.

1537
01:02:05,360 --> 01:02:07,630
I'm as nervous as I could be.

1538
01:02:08,300 --> 01:02:09,959
It feels like I'm getting judged...

1539
01:02:09,960 --> 01:02:11,600
for everything I've been building up until now.

1540
01:02:11,700 --> 01:02:13,700
I'm looking forward to it.

1541
01:02:14,470 --> 01:02:15,470
It makes me nervous too.

1542
01:02:17,170 --> 01:02:20,240
I prepared three kinds of cream donuts.

1543
01:02:20,640 --> 01:02:22,609
The dough is like a brioche.

1544
01:02:22,610 --> 01:02:24,479
I fried the soft dough.

1545
01:02:24,480 --> 01:02:27,310
It was then filled with soft cream.

1546
01:02:28,420 --> 01:02:29,449
(Pure Milk Donut)

1547
01:02:28,450 --> 01:02:30,219
I prepared Pure Milk Donut, Pistachio Raspberry Donut,

1548
01:02:29,450 --> 01:02:30,819
(Pistachio Raspberry Donut)

1549
01:02:30,220 --> 01:02:32,120
and Rocher Donut.

1550
01:02:30,820 --> 01:02:32,520
(Rocher Donut)

1551
01:02:32,520 --> 01:02:35,489
The one covered in chocolate is the Rocher Donut.

1552
01:02:35,490 --> 01:02:37,790
Does "Rocher" come from the famous chocolate brand?

1553
01:02:37,860 --> 01:02:41,329
That's right. "Rocher" means a rock.

1554
01:02:39,230 --> 01:02:40,959
(Rocher)

1555
01:02:40,960 --> 01:02:42,659
(It means a stone or a rock,)

1556
01:02:41,330 --> 01:02:43,799
I named it that way...

